# Svelte SEO Always-On Standards

- Treat all user-facing pages as SEO-sensitive unless explicitly marked internal.
- Prefer server-rendered, crawlable HTML for primary content.
- Keep metadata deterministic at initial render; avoid client-only title and description updates.
- Always include canonical URL strategy and avoid duplicate-content paths.
- Add descriptive title and meta description for each route-level page.
- Include Open Graph and Twitter metadata for share previews when relevant.
- Ensure heading structure is semantic and ordered (`h1` then nested headings).
- Use meaningful link text and alt text for crawlability and accessibility.
- For indexable pages, include structured data (JSON-LD) when it clarifies content type.
- Require internal linking from at least one crawlable path for new public pages.
- For new or changed public routes, ensure sitemap and robots expectations are reviewed.
- Avoid noindex on production content unless explicitly requested.
- Preserve performance-critical SEO signals (fast LCP, minimal layout shift, low blocking JS).

# Agent Execution Requirements

- When working with `.svelte` or `.svelte.ts/.svelte.js`, use the Svelte MCP workflow:
  1. `list-sections`
  2. `get-documentation` for relevant sections
  3. `svelte-autofixer` until no issues remain
- Keep edits aligned with project standards from `AGENTS.md`.
- Prefer small, focused helpers over long functions; keep logic compact.
